column137:
Video games are often targeted as the source of academic/social problems, but this is unlikely to be the case. It is far more likely in cases where video game usage is too high that their use is a response to academic/social problems, not the source.

How much is too much is relative to each individual and the utility they get from gaming. People with one-sided perspectives will never understand this.

My default desire is not always to be gaming, but to be social. This can be accomplished through gaming when you play with friends. Indeed, playing games online with friends from high school has been a great source of social support for me whereas I find BYU social life to be generally disappointing in my personal experience.
